          "text": "<p><b><font size=\"5\">\"Pediatric surgery\"</font></b></p>\n<hr>\n<h3><strong>UDT (Undescended Testis)</strong></h3>\n<ol>\n<li>\n<p><strong>Q:</strong> Best age for operation of UDT<br>\n<strong>A:</strong> 6 months</p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p><strong>Q:</strong> Most common site for UDT<br>\n<strong>A:</strong> Inguinal</p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p><strong>Q:</strong> Most common site for ectopic testis<br>\n<strong>A:</strong> Superficial inguinal pouch</p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p><strong>Q:</strong> Gubernaculum is responsible for<br>\n<strong>A:</strong> Mechanical descent</p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p><strong>Q:</strong> In palpable UDT<br>\n<strong>A:</strong> Laparoscopy</p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p><strong>Q:</strong> For proximal hypospadias, unilateral or perineal â€“ next step?<br>\n<strong>A:</strong> Karyotyping</p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p><strong>Q:</strong> Descent of testis<br>\n<strong>A:</strong> Mechanical, hormonal</p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p><strong>Q:</strong> Most common content of hernia of canal of Nuck<br>\n<strong>A:</strong> Ovaries</p>\n</li>\n</ol>\n<hr>\n<h3><strong>CHPS (Congenital Hypertrophic Pyloric Stenosis)</strong></h3>\n<ol start=\"9\">\n<li>\n<p><strong>Q:</strong> Vomiting in CHPS is<br>\n<strong>A:</strong> Non-bilious vomiting</p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p><strong>Q:</strong> Vomiting in pyloric atresia<br>\n<strong>A:</strong> Non-bilious vomiting</p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p><strong>Q:</strong> Metabolic disturbance in CHPS<br>\n<strong>A:</strong> Metabolic alkalosis</p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p><strong>Q:</strong> Most common cause of death in CHPS<br>\n<strong>A:</strong> Aspiration bronchopneumonia</p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p><strong>Statement:</strong> CHPS is not a surgical emergency</p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p><strong>Q:</strong> Investigation of choice in CHPS<br>\n<strong>A:</strong> U/S</p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p><strong>Q:</strong> Pyloric thickness<br>\n<strong>A:</strong> &gt;3 mm , â‰¥4mm (if 4mm â†’ false Ù…Ø´ ÙØ§Ù‡Ù… Ù‚ØµØ¯Ù‡ Ø§ÙŠÙ‡ØŸ )</p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p><strong>Q:</strong> Pyloric canal length<br>\n<strong>A:</strong> â‰¥13 mm</p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p><strong>Q:</strong> Gastrografin meal<br>\n<strong>A:</strong> Stomach dilation with delayed gastric emptying / delayed gastric emptying only / String sign</p></li>\n<li>\n<p><strong>Q:</strong> Common cause of projectile vomiting (alternative diagnosis)<br>\n<strong>A:</strong> Increased intracranial tension</p>\n</li>\n</ol>\n<hr>\n<h3><strong>Intussusception</strong></h3>\n<ol start=\"19\">\n<li>\n<p><strong>Q:</strong> Most common type of intussusception<br>\n<strong>A:</strong> Ileocecal</p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p><strong>Q:</strong> Rare type of intussusception<br>\n<strong>A:</strong> Reversed jejunogastric (post-gastrojejunostomy)</p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p><strong>Q:</strong> Presentation in pediatric intussusception<br>\n<strong>A:</strong> Blood &amp; mucus per rectum, red currant jelly stool, colicky abdominal pain</p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p><strong>Q:</strong> Abdominal mass<br>\n<strong>A:</strong> Sausage-shaped, supraumbilical</p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p><strong>Q:</strong> Investigation of choice in patients with intussusception<br>\n<strong>A:</strong>&nbsp;US<br></p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p><strong>Q:&nbsp; </strong>Passage of&nbsp;blood &amp; mucus per rectum<br>\n<strong>A:</strong> most common&nbsp;â†’ Dysentery<br>most serious&nbsp;â†’&nbsp; intussusception</p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p><strong>Q:</strong> Empty right iliac fossa<br>\n<strong>A:</strong> Dance sign</p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p><strong>Q:</strong> Early intussusception treatment<br>\n<strong>A:</strong> Pneumatic/hydrostatic reduction</p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p><strong>Q:</strong> Gastrografin enema signs<br><strong>A:</strong> Claw sign<br><br>by US&nbsp;â†’ target sign</p>\n</li>\n</ol>\n<hr>\n<h3><strong>Hirschsprungâ€™s Disease</strong></h3>\n<ol start=\"28\">\n<li>\n<p><strong>Q:</strong> Cardinal signs<br>\n<strong>A:</strong> Delayed passage of meconium &gt;24 hrs, distention, underweight, constipation, vomiting</p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p><strong>Q:</strong> Most accurate investigation<br>\n<strong>A:</strong> Anorectal biopsy /trans-iliac biopsy</p></li>\n<li>\n<p><strong>Q:</strong> Gastrografin enema&nbsp;<br>\n<strong>A:</strong>&nbsp;not accurate ,Loss of haustration, proximal dilation, distal collapse</p></li>\n<li>\n<p><strong>Q:</strong> Hirschsprung-associated enterocolitis<br>\n<strong>A:</strong>&nbsp;fever, hyperthermia, large distention, exclusive diarrhea or constipation</p>\n</li>\n</ol>\n<hr>\n<h3><strong>Neonatal Intestinal Obstruction (IO)</strong></h3>\n<ol start=\"32\">\n<li>\n<p><strong>Q:</strong> Cardinal signs<br>\n<strong>A:</strong> Absolute constipation, abdominal pain, distention, vomiting</p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p><strong>Q:</strong> Double bubble sign<br>\n<strong>A:</strong> Duodenal atresia</p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p><strong>Q:</strong> Single bubble sign<br>\n<strong>A:</strong> Pyloric atresia</p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p><strong>Q:</strong> Triple bubble sign<br>\n<strong>A:</strong>&nbsp;upper Jejunal atresia</p></li>\n<li>\n<p><strong>Q:</strong> Bilious vomiting indicates<br>\n<strong>A:</strong>&nbsp;IO</p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p><strong>Q:</strong>&nbsp;Malrotation&nbsp;<br>\n<strong>A:</strong>&nbsp;gastrograffin&nbsp;â†’ DJ to the right&nbsp;</p>\n</li><li><p>Investigation of choice in imperforate anus<br><b>A:&nbsp;</b>Lateral table test</p></li>\n<li>\n<p><strong>Q:</strong> Patient with no anus<br>\n<strong>A:&nbsp;</strong>Invertogram<br><br><img src=\"https://i.postimg.cc/6pKzTysf/1.png\"></p></li>\n</ol>\n<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<img src=\"https://i.postimg.cc/k5SjsShB/2.png\"><br>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;<img src=\"https://i.postimg.cc/Zqp6xqX1/3.png\"><br>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<img src=\"https://i.postimg.cc/ZnR92YDY/4.png\"><br>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;<img src=\"https://i.postimg.cc/qBb6nnzN/5.png\"><br><br></p>\n        \n    ",
